<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-21T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-21T04:00:00-05:00" n="378" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d378">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/12571: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                                </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-21T18:00:00+09:00">December 21, 1918—6 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received December 21—12:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your telegram December 19, 4 p.m. Since the publication of the interview
                            reported in my telegram of November 3, 1 p.m.,<note n="3" xml:id="d378fn3">
                                <ref target="frus1918Supp01v01#pg_661">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, supp. 1, vol.
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 661</ref>.</note> Okuma has
                            made no public statement with reference to Japan’s ambitions in the
                            South Sea Islands. Reports in the American press are probably based on a
                            special interview granted their representative which were [<hi rend="italic">was</hi>] not given out in Japan.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>